Les années sauterelles de l'Amérique Latine
Les mauvaises nouvelles continuent de s'accumuler ces jours-ci en Amérique Latine.
Les conditions économiques se détériorent quasiment partout, la cohésion sociale s'effiloche et l'instabilité politique grandit.
Ce n'est guère étonnant puisque la grande majorité des pays d'Amérique Latine ont passé les vingt dernières années à aller nulle part.
Les capitaux ont été vendus et les dettes nationales démesurément augmentées, mais rien de durable et de bénéfique n'a été obtenu.
Ces années ont vraiment été mangées par les sauterelles.
Au cours des 20 dernières années, la croissance annuelle du PNB par habitant en Amérique Latine a atteint la moyenne de 0,35 %.
A cette vitesse, une économie mettrait 200 années à doubler.
En Asie, le niveau de vie double chaque décennie.
Avec une croissance tellement anémique, comment l'Amérique Latine peut-elle espérer rivaliser dans le commerce mondial à part à travers une hausse des salaires toujours timide ?
The economic stagnation stems from bad governance, not from bad luck.
If Latin America does not change, it may start looking more and more like Africa - a region composed of weak states with large informal economies and widespread poverty.
Four factors have put it on this path.
Firstly, in the rush to privatization, everything from public services to manufacturing industries was sold off at auction.
For a brief moment, capital sales helped balance national budgets and also provided resources to support consumption.
Finalement, les revenus dérivés de la privatisation ont produit peu dans le cadre d'une meilleure infrastructure ou d'exportations plus compétitives.
Pire encore, la liquidation des biens de l'état a été accompagnée d'un emprunt externe massif.
Dans certains cas, notamment en Argentine, l'emprunt réalisé par les acheteurs nationaux a épuisé toutes les gammes disponibles de crédit.
D'autres pays ne sont pas tombés au niveau de l'Argentine, mais la solvabilité représente un problème dans quasiment tous les pays d'Amérique Latine.
Deuxièmement, étant donné que la réforme n'a pas amené la prospérité, la région en est devenue écoeurée.
The influx of capital produced an effect of wealth, but only as long as it existed.
When the money stopped flowing freely, the wealth dried up.
No sensible politician would commit to another decade of structural reforms that would stretch the patience of middle-class Latin Americans beyond the limits of electoral survival.
But without a greater number of deep reforms, too few prerequisites for economic growth will be met to attract investments, without which no growth is possible.
This development dilemma signals the third factor: incompetent policies.
The governments that operated on technocratic lines and viewed economic growth as a rising tide lifting all boats have disappeared.
In Argentina, clumsy presidents follow one another.
Institutions are brought down, property rights are questioned, and a random and even more corrupt redistribution effort is underway.
Peru and Venezuela are not much luckier; Brazil may soon take the same path.
The popularity of Luiz Inácio da Silva and his team, who lead opinion polls ahead of Brazil's presidential elections, indicates that a large part of Latin America's population is prepared to reject traditional governments.
Lula and his party are so far from the prevailing economic thinking and politics that capital has already begun to flee - even though the elections are only a few months away.
In Mexico, democratization has brought greater stability, but this could turn out to be fleeting.
The peso is now excessively overvalued.
If the external balance deteriorates further, the economy risks a hard landing.
As for all the good news about Mexico's nascent democracy, its president is starting to justify the fears that existed about him: no vision, no Congress, and no team knowing what it needs to do.
The last factor relates to the desperately low savings rate that is endemic to the Americas.
In fact, this is the economically sound result because where there is little savings, there is little investment – and little base for accumulating capital and increasing productivity.
Venezuela now sighs after the fat years of the 1970s of OPEC – to which it did not participate, having neglected to develop its oil industry.
The wealth of Argentina now takes vacations in Miami, perhaps for good.
Brazil and Mexico are perfect examples of countries that have sold their assets and borrowed rather than saved.
The contrast with Asia is striking.
Take China, where savings and investment rates reach nearly 40%, where the current account is in surplus, and where there is no public debt.
Government institutions favor the market and the population is well-educated, disciplined, and flexible in learning.
Rewards for taking risks and initiative are immediate and highly motivating.
We cannot deny that China remains a poor country.
His per capita PNB represents only half of Brazil's.
But with growth in China's coastal region at about 15% annually, can it seriously be doubted that within the next 15 years, it will surpass Brazil?
In China, despite all the huge problems encountered, things continue to proceed correctly, first due to the massive inflow of foreign direct investments and the imminent benefits of joining the WTO.
In Latin America, things continue to disintegrate: governments are backing away from reform, and the economy is losing ground against the rest of the world.
Latin America was doing well when unregulated funds were flowing in, but these times are largely over.
We must therefore expect much worse economic, social, and political developments in the years to come.
Demagogues such as Hugo Chavez in Venezuela or Carlos Menem – a presidential candidate in Argentina once again – may appear to be a bad joke, but anyone concerned about the fate of Latin America should not laugh at them.
